<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1907,2004]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,392]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,320,1907,1932]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Identification.</emphasis>
Distinguishing 
<taxonomicName box="[510,614,1908,1932]" class="Reptilia" family="Homalopsidae" genus="Cerberus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[510,614,1908,1932]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Cerberus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species on the basis of morphology alone can be difficult which in part accounts for the fact that 
<taxonomicName authority="Schneider, 1799" authorityName="Schneider" authorityYear="1799" box="[439,576,1944,1968]" class="Reptilia" family="Elapidae" genus="Hydrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rynchops">
<emphasis box="[439,576,1944,1968]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">C. rynchops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been described 
<number box="[804,831,1943,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="11.0">11</number>
separate times since 
<number box="[1072,1131,1943,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1799.0">1799</number>
. 
<tableCitation box="[1143,1227,1943,1967]" captionStart="TABLE 2. A" captionStartId="7.[151,244,439,464]" captionTargetBox="[180,1419,497,1225]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. A comparison of morphological characters commonly used to distinguish five species of Cerberus." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF381796FFBAFFEEFF60FE65FAAA9B93" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" tableUuid="DF381796FFBAFFEEFF60FE65FAAA9B93">
Table 
<number box="[1213,1227,1943,1967]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="2.0">2</number>
</tableCitation>
summarizes some of the morphological data discussed here that can be used to separate these taxa. The variable dorsal scale row counts within and between species, the fragmentation of head shields, and the relatively similar coloration and pattern, make these species somewhat cryptic. This can be highlighted by Loveridge’s (
<number box="[1147,1205,188,212]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1948.0">1948</number>
) confusion when he named the New 
<collectingCountry box="[345,426,223,247]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Guinea</collectingCountry>
population 
<taxonomicName box="[566,950,224,248]" class="Reptilia" family="Homalopsidae" genus="Cerberus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="rynchops" subSpecies="novaeguineae">
<emphasis box="[566,950,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Cerberus rynchops novaeguineae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
instead of recognizing its morphology as more similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[332,430,260,284]" class="Reptilia" family="Homalopsidae" genus="Homalopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[332,430,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and 
<bibRefCitation box="[493,723,260,284]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refString="Cogger, H. G., Cameron, E. E. &amp; Cogger, H. M. (1983) Zoological Catalogue of Australia. Vol. 1. Amphibia and Reptilia. Australia Government Publishing Service, Canberra, 313 pp." type="book">
Cogger 
<emphasis box="[584,634,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[657,715,260,284]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1983.0">1983</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
synonymizing 
<taxonomicName box="[898,1108,260,284]" class="Reptilia" family="Homalopsidae" genus="Cerberus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[898,1108,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Cerberus australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1164,1379,260,284]" class="Reptilia" family="Homalopsidae" genus="Cerberus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rynchops">
<emphasis box="[1164,1379,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Cerberus rynchops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, two species that differ genetically by 6.4–9.5% (
<bibRefCitation author="Alfaro" box="[707,945,295,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refString="Alfaro, M. E., Karns, D. R., Voris, H K., Abernathy, E. &amp; Sellins, S. L. (2004) Phylogeny of Cerberus (Serpentes: Homalopsinae) and phylogeny of Cerberus rynchops: diversification of a coastal marine snake in Southeast Asia. Journal of Biogeography, 31, 1277 - 1292." type="journal article" year="2004">
Alfaro 
<emphasis box="[800,860,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[884,945,295,319]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The five species recognized here are morphologically distinct, with the differences often subtle but consistent. Four of these species have been previously compared using mitochondrial and nuclear genes (
<bibRefCitation author="Alfaro" box="[840,1044,367,392]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refString="Alfaro, M. E., Karns, D. R., Voris, H K., Abernathy, E. &amp; Sellins, S. L. (2004) Phylogeny of Cerberus (Serpentes: Homalopsinae) and phylogeny of Cerberus rynchops: diversification of a coastal marine snake in Southeast Asia. Journal of Biogeography, 31, 1277 - 1292." type="journal article" year="2004">
Alfaro 
<emphasis box="[922,970,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[985,1044,367,391]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2004.2008">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Alfaro" box="[1055,1116,367,391]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refString="Alfaro, M. E., Karns, D. R., Voris, H. K., Brock, C. D. &amp; Stuart, B. L. (2008) Phylogeny, evolutionary history, and biogeography of Oriental-Australian rear-fanged water snakes (Colubroidea: Homalopsidae) inferred from mitochondrial and nuclear DNA sequences. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 46, 576 - 593." type="journal article" year="2008">2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
